The fluorescence microscopy studies revealed that C-CDs differentially stained the Saccharomyces cerevisiae yeast cell. Fig. 8
                         exhibited intense blue, green and red fluorescence at 405 nm, 488 nm and 561 nm excitation wavelengths respectively. The results shows that control sample do not have any fluorescence since it is not treated with C-CDs. The blue, green and red emission is observed in cells, treated with C-CDs. This is because, the hydrophilic CDs were spread into the cell membrane, cytoplasmic area. Eventually come to the conclusion that the C-CDs has strong ability to stain the bacterial cells. The staining may be due to the endocytosis mechanism through their homogeneous distributions inside the cell [24]. In addition to this, we examined the cytotoxicity of synthesized C-CDs with varying concentration in yeast cells. The results indicate that, the optical density at different concentration of the CDs were not significantly different from blank, indicating that the as-prepared CDs have almost no cytotoxicity up to 400 μL. (Fig. 9
                        ) These preludes demonstrate that the multicolor C-CDs exhibited very excellent biocompatibility and acted as benign candidates for yeast cell imaging, which becomes alternative to hazardous semiconductor quantum dots.
